properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A strong arctic ridge of high pressure across northern Yukon is giving temperatures near minus 44C this morning. Light winds at times will result in wind chill values in the minus 50's. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 15 to 25 cm is expected. Locations: southern Avalon Peninsula. Time span: early Christmas Eve morning until late Christmas Eve night. Remarks: Snow, at times heavy, will begin early in the morning on Christmas Eve and continue until into Christmas Eve night. Snow may mix with rain at times over extreme southern areas. Strong northerly winds will also develop on Christmas Eve night resulting in areas of blowing snow. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall expected. Total snowfall: 10 to 20 cm with more possible. Locations: northeastern and eastern Newfoundland. Maximum wind gusts: northwesterly 60 to 80 km/h on Christmas Day. Time span: tonight, Christmas Eve and Christmas Day. Remarks: Snow is expected to begin to begin Christmas Eve morning and continue into Christmas Eve night. Snow is expected to become more intermittent on Christmas Day, but northwesterly winds are expected to increase to strong by early on Christmas Day. Fresh snow and strong winds will make for poor driving conditions for Christmas Day. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heavy snowfall with blowing snow is expected. Total snowfall: 25 cm or more. Maximum wind gusts: northerly 80 km/h. Time span: Christmas Eve morning until late Christmas Eve night. Remarks: snow, at times heavy, will begin Christmas Eve morning and continue until late Christmas Eve night. Strong easterly winds gusting to 60 km/h will develop during the afternoon on Christmas Eve and further increase to strong northerlies gusting to 80 km/h Christmas Eve night. The combination of fresh snowfall and strong winds will create poor visibility in blowing snow. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2019-12-24T06:15:37-00:00

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 20 cm is expected. Locations; south coast of Newfoundland from Burgeo to Francois. Time span: this evening until Christmas Eve morning. Remarks: scattered flurries will transition to snow, at times heavy, by mid-evening. Snowfall rates will begin to ease again in the morning. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
